  "text": "To compare Ca 2+ -current density, we plotted the peak Ca 2+ current (elicited by 10-mV pulses) versus nerve terminal capacitance (capacitance is proportional to membrane area) (Fig. 3c) . All recordings were made in 10 mM Ca 2+ so that wild-type and knockout terminals could be compared. Linear regression yielded a steeper slope for wild-type nerve terminals. The average Ca 2+ -current density was more than threefold greater for wild types (wild type, 100.8 ± 18.3 pA/pF; knockout, 31.1 ± 5.0 pA/pF; P ¼ 0.003). In both wild-type and knockout nerve terminals, Ca 2+ current inactivated with a time constant of B40 ms. Thus, nerve terminals lacking Syt IV have much lower Ca 2+ current per unit area of plasma membrane, but the Ca 2+ channels have the same activation and inactivation properties. [CITATION_1] . We made recordings of Ca 2+ current and capacitance in wild-type and Syt IV knockout nerve terminals (Fig. 4a) .",
